64struct sctp_vrf {
65 LIST_ENTRY (sctp_vrf) next_vrf;
66 struct sctp_ifalist *vrf_addr_hash;
67 struct sctp_ifnlist ifnlist;
68 uint32_t vrf_id;
69 uint32_t tbl_id_v4; /* default v4 table id */
70 uint32_t tbl_id_v6; /* default v6 table id */
71 uint32_t total_ifa_count;
72 u_long vrf_addr_hashmark;
73 uint32_t refcount;
74};
75
76struct sctp_ifn {
77 struct sctp_ifalist ifalist;
78 struct sctp_vrf *vrf;
79 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_ifn) next_ifn;
80 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_ifn) next_bucket;
81 void *ifn_p; /* never access without appropriate lock */
82 uint32_t ifn_mtu;
83 uint32_t ifn_type;
84 uint32_t ifn_index; /* shorthand way to look at ifn for reference */
85 uint32_t refcount; /* number of reference held should be >= ifa_count */
86 uint32_t ifa_count; /* IFA's we hold (in our list - ifalist)*/
87 uint32_t num_v6; /* number of v6 addresses */
88 uint32_t num_v4; /* number of v4 addresses */
89 uint32_t registered_af; /* registered address family for i/f events */
90 char ifn_name[SCTP_IFNAMSIZ];
91};
92
93/* SCTP local IFA flags */
94#define SCTP_ADDR_VALID 0x00000001 /* its up and active */
95#define SCTP_BEING_DELETED 0x00000002 /* being deleted,
96 * when refcount = 0. Note
97 * that it is pulled from the ifn list
98 * and ifa_p is nulled right away but
99 * it cannot be freed until the last *net
100 * pointing to it is deleted.
101 */
102#define SCTP_ADDR_DEFER_USE 0x00000004 /* Hold off using this one */
103#define SCTP_ADDR_IFA_UNUSEABLE 0x00000008
104
105struct sctp_ifa {
106 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_ifa) next_ifa;
107 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_ifa) next_bucket;
108 struct sctp_ifn *ifn_p; /* back pointer to parent ifn */
109 void *ifa; /* pointer to ifa, needed for flag
110 * update for that we MUST lock
111 * appropriate locks. This is for V6.
112 */
113 union sctp_sockstore address;
114 uint32_t refcount; /* number of folks referring to this */
115 uint32_t flags;
116 uint32_t localifa_flags;
117 uint32_t vrf_id; /* vrf_id of this addr (for deleting) */
118 uint8_t src_is_loop;
119 uint8_t src_is_priv;
120 uint8_t src_is_glob;
121 uint8_t resv;
122};

124struct sctp_laddr {
125 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_laddr) sctp_nxt_addr; /* next in list */
126 struct sctp_ifa *ifa;
127 uint32_t action; /* Used during asconf and adding
128 * if no-zero src-addr selection will
129 * not consider this address.
130 */
131 struct timeval start_time; /* time when this address was created */
132};

164
165 /*-
166 * The TCP model represents a substantial overhead in that we get an
167 * additional hash table to keep explicit connections in. The
168 * listening TCP endpoint will exist in the usual ephash above and
169 * accept only INIT's. It will be incapable of sending off an INIT.
170 * When a dg arrives we must look in the normal ephash. If we find a
171 * TCP endpoint that will tell us to go to the specific endpoint
172 * hash and re-hash to find the right assoc/socket. If we find a UDP
173 * model socket we then must complete the lookup. If this fails,
174 * i.e. no association can be found then we must continue to see if
175 * a sctp_peeloff()'d socket is in the tcpephash (a spun off socket
176 * acts like a TCP model connected socket).
177 */
178 struct sctppcbhead *sctp_tcpephash;
179 u_long hashtcpmark;
180 uint32_t hashtblsize;
181
182 struct sctp_vrflist *sctp_vrfhash;
183 u_long hashvrfmark;
184
185 struct sctp_ifnlist *vrf_ifn_hash;
186 u_long vrf_ifn_hashmark;

348/*-
349 * Here we have all the relevant information for each SCTP entity created. We
350 * will need to modify this as approprate. We also need to figure out how to
351 * access /dev/random.
352 */
353struct sctp_pcb {
354 unsigned int time_of_secret_change; /* number of seconds from
355 * timeval.tv_sec */
356 uint32_t secret_key[SCTP_HOW_MANY_SECRETS][SCTP_NUMBER_OF_SECRETS];
357 unsigned int size_of_a_cookie;
358
359 uint32_t sctp_timeoutticks[SCTP_NUM_TMRS];
360 uint32_t sctp_minrto;
361 uint32_t sctp_maxrto;
362 uint32_t initial_rto;
363 uint32_t initial_init_rto_max;
364
365 unsigned int sctp_sack_freq;
366 uint32_t sctp_sws_sender;
367 uint32_t sctp_sws_receiver;
368
369 uint32_t sctp_default_cc_module;
370 uint32_t sctp_default_ss_module;
371 /* authentication related fields */
372 struct sctp_keyhead shared_keys;
373 sctp_auth_chklist_t *local_auth_chunks;
374 sctp_hmaclist_t *local_hmacs;
375 uint16_t default_keyid;
376 uint32_t default_mtu;
377
378 /* various thresholds */
379 /* Max times I will init at a guy */
380 uint16_t max_init_times;
381
382 /* Max times I will send before we consider someone dead */
383 uint16_t max_send_times;
384
385 uint16_t def_net_failure;
386
387 uint16_t def_net_pf_threshold;
388
389 /* number of streams to pre-open on a association */
390 uint16_t pre_open_stream_count;
391 uint16_t max_open_streams_intome;
392
393 /* random number generator */
394 uint32_t random_counter;
395 uint8_t random_numbers[SCTP_SIGNATURE_ALOC_SIZE];
396 uint8_t random_store[SCTP_SIGNATURE_ALOC_SIZE];
397
398 /*
399 * This timer is kept running per endpoint. When it fires it will
400 * change the secret key. The default is once a hour
401 */
402 struct sctp_timer signature_change;
403
404 uint32_t def_cookie_life;
405 /* defaults to 0 */
406 uint32_t auto_close_time;
407 uint32_t initial_sequence_debug;
408 uint32_t adaptation_layer_indicator;
409 uint8_t adaptation_layer_indicator_provided;
410 uint32_t store_at;
411 uint32_t max_burst;
412 uint32_t fr_max_burst;
413#ifdef INET6
414 uint32_t default_flowlabel;
415#endif
416 uint8_t default_dscp;
417 char current_secret_number;
418 char last_secret_number;
419 uint16_t port; /* remote UDP encapsulation port */
420};

593struct sctp_tcb {
594 struct socket *sctp_socket; /* back pointer to socket */
595 struct sctp_inpcb *sctp_ep; /* back pointer to ep */
596 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_tcb) sctp_tcbhash; /* next link in hash
597 * table */
598 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_tcb) sctp_tcblist; /* list of all of the
599 * TCB's */
600 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_tcb) sctp_tcbasocidhash; /* next link in asocid
601 * hash table
602 */
603 LIST_ENTRY(sctp_tcb) sctp_asocs; /* vtag hash list */
604 struct sctp_block_entry *block_entry; /* pointer locked by socket
605 * send buffer */
606 struct sctp_association asoc;
607 /*-
608 * freed_by_sorcv_sincelast is protected by the sockbuf_lock NOT the
609 * tcb_lock. Its special in this way to help avoid extra mutex calls
610 * in the reading of data.
611 */
612 uint32_t freed_by_sorcv_sincelast;
613 uint32_t total_sends;
614 uint32_t total_recvs;
615 int freed_from_where;
616 uint16_t rport; /* remote port in network format */
617 uint16_t resv;
618#if defined(__FreeBSD__) && !defined(__Userspace__)
619 struct mtx tcb_mtx;
620 struct mtx tcb_send_mtx;
621#elif defined(SCTP_PROCESS_LEVEL_LOCKS)
622 userland_mutex_t tcb_mtx;

624#elif defined(__APPLE__) && !defined(__Userspace__)

627#elif defined(_WIN32) && !defined(__Userspace__)

631#endif

637};
